                                                                                                                                    StanChart operating profit rises to $690m

              
	Mumbai, Feb. 26 (PTI): A robust growth in its key businesses  corporate finance, SME and wealth management  has pushed up Standard Chartered Banks operating profit at $690 million against $403 million in the year-ago period, a rise of 71 per cent.
    
	The growth, which was led by a 60 per cent increase in its revenues, has made India the banks second largest market in the world after Hong Kong, where its revenues for the year stood at $1,193 million for the year, the bank said. India contributes 17 per cent to the groups global profits, the banks regional chief executive Neeraj Swaroop said today.
    
	The growth momentum is strong. We should post a strong growth this year as well, Swaroop said.
    
	The banks profit was slightly affected by the sharp depreciation in the dollar, but the impact was not severe, he said.
    
	Citing high growth in the middle markets and corporate segments through its wholesale banking service, Swaroop said the bank expected a robust expansion in the corporate client section this year.
    
	The bank plans to give a strong thrust to its private banking and cross-border transaction businesses this year.
    
	We plan to scale up our private banking business in the country. We will also give a strong thrust to cross-border financing activities, Swaroop said. 
                                                                
